Here's how to make your page theme-aware:

## XAML with `AppThemeBinding`

Replace every hardcoded color with an `AppThemeBinding` that provides both a light and dark value:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.MainPage"
             BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=#1C1C1E}">

    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="20" Spacing="15">

        <Label Text="Welcome!"
               FontSize="28"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#333333, Dark=#FFFFFF}" />

        <Label Text="This page follows your system theme."
               FontSize="16"
               TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#666666, Dark=#AAAAAA}" />

        <Button Text="Get Started"
                TextColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=White, Dark=White}"
                BackgroundColor="{AppThemeBinding Light=#2196F3, Dark=#BB86FC}" />

    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

The OS theme is detected automatically — no extra wiring needed. When the user toggles dark mode in system settings, every `AppThemeBinding` re-evaluates instantly.

## C# Alternative

Use the `SetAppThemeColor` extension method for colors, or the generic `SetAppTheme<T>` for any property:

```csharp
public class MainPage : ContentPage
{
    public MainPage()
    {
        this.SetAppThemeColor(BackgroundColorProperty, Colors.White, Color.FromArgb("#1C1C1E"));

        var title = new Label { Text = "Welcome!", FontSize = 28 };
        title.SetAppThemeColor(Label.TextColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#333333"), Colors.White);

        var subtitle = new Label { Text = "This page follows your system theme.", FontSize = 16 };
        subtitle.SetAppThemeColor(Label.TextColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#666666"), Color.FromArgb("#AAAAAA"));

        var button = new Button { Text = "Get Started", TextColor = Colors.White };
        button.SetAppThemeColor(Button.BackgroundColorProperty, Color.FromArgb("#2196F3"), Color.FromArgb("#BB86FC"));

        Content = new VerticalStackLayout
        {
            Padding = 20, Spacing = 15,
            Children = { title, subtitle, button }
        };
    }
}
```

## Key points

- **`AppThemeBinding`** gives you automatic light/dark — zero event handling needed.
- **Android pitfall** — ensure `MainActivity` includes `ConfigChanges.UiMode` or theme changes cause a full activity restart instead of a smooth switch.
- **Scaling up** — if you end up repeating the same colors everywhere, move them into `ResourceDictionary` files (one per theme) and reference them with `DynamicResource`. That centralizes your palette and makes future changes easier.
